ds to change over time, how negation is acquired by children, how it is processed by adults, and how its expression changes over time. Specific chapters offer focused empirical studies of negative polarity, pleonastic negation, and negative/quantifier scope interaction, as well as detailed examinations of the form and function of sentential negation in modern Romance languages and Classical Japanese.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxNegatives. 0aNegation (Logic) 0aNegation (Logic). 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aPsycholinguistik. 4aSemantik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive Linguistics.  aNegation.  aPsycholinguistics.  aSemantics.1 aAuwera, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahl, Östen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimroth, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFein, Ofer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiora, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoeksema, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Laurence  R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Laurence R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKato, Yasuhiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetuki, Nili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeukom-Hermann, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStern, Pnina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTottie, Gunnel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook pac